7-20180321-024606"/></CodeI><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:niex"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="ncat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Content Types</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:niex"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:nitv"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfact"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Factiva Filters</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:niex"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:nitv"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfcpex"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">C&amp;E Executive News Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:niex"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:nitv"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">ST</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">What does it take to be a neurosurgeon? Q&amp;A with NNI medical director Ng Wai Hoe</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Q: Why do you shave the head just before the surgery?</Para><Para>A: We shave the head in the operating theatre because if you shave too early you may nick the skin, and risk an infection.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>If the patient is a young woman, I will ask if she is concerned about losing her hair - for some patients it's their main concern.</Para><Para>We can do a minimal shave so the patient can comb their hair over it and no one even knows they went for surgery. This is a bit harder and the patient will need to look after the wound a bit better.</Para><Para>But it's important that the patients feel good psychologically, and that we're treating them as humans rather than just patients.</Para><Para>Losing your hair can be quite dehumanising.</Para><Para>Q: What is the hardest part of awake brain surgery?</Para><Para>A: The toughest part of the procedure, the critical part, is when we're reaching the edge of the tumour and the critical part of the brain that controls language or movement, for example. We need to make a judgement call, to continue, stop or slow down.</Para><Para>Q: What else do you take into account since the patient is awake?</Para><Para>A: We have to be sensitive to the fact that the patient is awake. We are extra careful about not creating noise, and there's no talking about holidays and vacations.</Para><Para>Q: Does it matter if the patient is right or left-handed?</Para><Para>A: In more than 95 per cent of right-handed patients, the critical area for speech is located in the left side of the brain.</Para><Para>For left-handers, it's not so clear cut. For about half of them, it is in the right cerebral hemisphere, for 25 per cent, it is on the left and for the rest, it's in both the right and left sides of the brain.</Para><Para>So we have to do a functional MRI to make sure if they are right, left or co-language dominant.</Para><Para>Q: You and your team are doing a trial on using fluorescent dye to highlight a brain tumour. How does this work?</Para><Para>A: Because the brain is so unique and critical to the body, it is like a sanctuary that chemicals and toxins cannot enter. This is why blood vessels that flow into the brain have tight junctions that do not allow access. When a tumour happens, these gaps widen and the dye is allowed in. With the help of a blue filter, the tumour then lights up in bright yellow.</Para><Para>Q: What are the qualities needed to be a successful neurosurgeon?</Para><Para>A: You need to consider that it's tough work. You need a lot of mental and physical resilience and the ability to manage adverse situations. Things can happen very fast and you do not have the luxury of time when it's a matter of life and death.</Para><Para>And because surgery takes a long time, you need to be in good health, and be able to function on little sleep. Be prepared to skip meals and have a strong bladder. You don't need to be a genius but you have to be cool-headed, be able to think on your feet to make split-second decisions and be good at multi-tasking.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Chang Ai-Lien </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

